## PATCH /api/users/{id}/status  (admin only)

Scenarios 7 and 8. ACC-008: only an Administrator can deactivate or
reactivate an account. Same endpoint handles both directions — ACC-006
means status is always exactly one of these two values, so there's no
separate "reactivate" verb, just the target state.

Request — deactivate Chen (scenario 7):
```json
PATCH /api/users/cccccccc-cccc-4ccc-8ccc-cccccccccccc/status
Authorization: Bearer <jwt for admin>
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "status": "DEACTIVATED"
}
```

Response — 200 OK:
```json
{
  "id": "cccccccc-cccc-4ccc-8ccc-cccccccccccc",
  "status": "DEACTIVATED",
  "updatedAt": "2026-07-13T10:00:00Z"
}
```

Request — reactivate Chen later (scenario 8; see
Archive/Development/Backend/Discussion/Stage-1 Q2 for exactly what this
does and doesn't change — role is untouched, past orders were never
altered in the first place, no notification fires):
```json
PATCH /api/users/cccccccc-cccc-4ccc-8ccc-cccccccccccc/status
Authorization: Bearer <jwt for admin>
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "status": "ACTIVE"
}
```

Response — 200 OK:
```json
{
  "id": "cccccccc-cccc-4ccc-8ccc-cccccccccccc",
  "status": "ACTIVE",
  "updatedAt": "2026-07-13T11:00:00Z"
}
```

Response — 403 Forbidden (a Customer attempting this on any account,
including their own — ACC-008: "A Customer cannot deactivate their own
account or anyone else's."):
```json
{
  "error": {
    "code": "FORBIDDEN",
    "message": "Only an Administrator can change an account's status."
  }
}
```

